SIMPLE: runner
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Runner
<hw>Run"ner</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From
<er>Run</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, runs; a
racer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A detective.</def> <mark>[Slang, Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Dickens.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A messenger.</def> <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A smuggler.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <rj><au>R.
North.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>One employed to solicit patronage, as for a
steamboat, hotel, shop, etc.</def> <mark>[Cant, U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A slender trailing branch which
takes root at the joints or end and there forms new plants, as in the
strawberry and the common cinquefoil.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>The rotating stone of a set of millstones.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A rope rove through a block and
used to increase the mechanical power of a tackle.</def>
<rj><au>Totten.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1262 --></p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>One of the pieces on which a sled or sleigh slides;
also the part or blade of a skate which slides on the ice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Founding)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A horizontal
channel in a mold, through which the metal flows to the cavity formed by
the pattern; also, the waste metal left in such a channel.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>A trough or channel for leading molten metal from a
furnace to a ladle, mold, or pig bed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>The movable piece to which the ribs of an umbrella
are attached.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A food fish (<spn>Elagatis
pinnulatus</spn>) of Florida and the West Indies; -- called also
<altname>skipjack</altname>, <altname>shoemaker</altname>, and
<altname>yellowtail</altname>. The name alludes to its rapid successive
leaps from the water.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any cursorial bird.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A movable slab or
rubber used in grinding or polishing a surface of stone.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>A tool on which lenses are fastened in a group, for
polishing or grinding.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Runnet</ent>⟦br⟧
